Project Foundations for Data Science: FoodHub Data Analysis¶

Marks: 40 points

Context¶

The number of restaurants in New York is increasing day by day. Lots of students and busy professionals rely on those restaurants due to their hectic lifestyles. Online food delivery service is a great option for them. It provides them with good food from their favorite restaurants. A food aggregator company FoodHub offers access to multiple restaurants through a single smartphone app.

The app allows the restaurants to receive a direct online order from a customer. The app assigns a delivery person from the company to pick up the order after it is confirmed by the restaurant. The delivery person then uses the map to reach the restaurant and waits for the food package. Once the food package is handed over to the delivery person, he/she confirms the pick-up in the app and travels to the customer's location to deliver the food. The delivery person confirms the drop-off in the app after delivering the food package to the customer. The customer can rate the order in the app. The food aggregator earns money by collecting a fixed margin of the delivery order from the restaurants.

Objective¶

The food aggregator company has stored the data of the different orders made by the registered customers in their online portal. They want to analyze the data to get a fair idea about the demand of different restaurants which will help them in enhancing their customer experience. Suppose you are a Data Scientist at Foodhub and the Data Science team has shared some of the key questions that need to be answered. Perform the data analysis to find answers to these questions that will help the company to improve the business.

Data Description¶

The data contains the different data related to a food order. The detailed data dictionary is given below.

Data Dictionary¶

  • order_id: Unique ID of the order
  • customer_id: ID of the customer who ordered the food
  • restaurant_name: Name of the restaurant
  • cuisine_type: Cuisine ordered by the customer
  • cost_of_the_order: Cost of the order
  • day_of_the_week: Indicates whether the order is placed on a weekday or weekend (The weekday is from Monday to Friday and the weekend is Saturday and Sunday)
  • rating: Rating given by the customer out of 5
  • food_preparation_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the restaurant to prepare the food. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the restaurant's order confirmation and the delivery person's pick-up confirmation.
  • delivery_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the delivery person to deliver the food package. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the delivery person's pick-up confirmation and drop-off information

The last part of that code is to save the results as a new variable called df_greater_than_20 so it can be used in further analysis.

Finding the total percentage: This code is telling Python to find all of the number of rows within the newly created variable (df_greater_than_20) and divide that by the total number of rows in the whole dataframe; then multiply by 100 to get a percentage

Correlation among variables¶

In [44]:
# Create a heatmap

sns.heatmap(df[col_list].corr(), annot=True, vmin=-1, vmax=1, fmt=".2f", cmap="Spectral")

The Heatmap shows the correlation between several variables. This correlation can be used to quickly identify if one variable has an impact on another. The scale represents the level of correlation with 0 being no correlation. As the values increase from 0, the correlation increases (positive correlation. Values less than 0 indicate a negative correlation. The results of this analysis indicate there is not a strong correlation between cost of the order, food preparation time, or delivery time.

Explain the code:

  1. Filter out the 'Not Given' ratings
  • the code is telling Python to find the 'rating' column within the df dataframe. Then find the values 'Not given' within that dataframe. Make a copy of the dataframe and call it df_rated and copy over the results but exclude all the values 'Not given'.
  1. Converting the values in the 'rating' column to integers
  • the code is telling Python to find the 'rating' column within the new variable df_rated and cast them as type integer. Place these new results intoe the 'rating' column within the df_rated dataframe
  1. Create a new dataframe df_rating_count
  • the code is asking Python to take the columns 'restaurant_name' and 'rating' from the df_rated dataframe and sort the values in descending order. Group the results by restaurant name. Once the list is made, reset the index so the row numbers are reassigned for this dataframe (starting at 0)

Question 14: The company charges the restaurant 25% on the orders having cost greater than 20 dollars and 15% on the orders having cost greater than 5 dollars. Find the net revenue generated by the company across all orders¶

In [58]:
# Create a function to calculate revenue
def compute_rev(x):
    if x > 20:
        return x*0.25
    elif x > 5:
        return x*0.15
    else:
        return x*0

df['Revenue'] = df['cost_of_the_order'].apply(compute_rev)

Question 15: The company wants to analyze the total time required to deliver the food. What percentage of orders take more than 60 minutes to get delivered from the time the order is placed? (The food has to be prepared and then delivered)¶

In [62]:
df['total_time'] = df['food_preparation_time'] + df['delivery_time']


## Write the code below to find the percentage of orders that have more than 60 minutes of total delivery time (see Question 9 for reference)

# Get orders that have more than 60 minutes of total delivery time
df_greater_than_60 = df[df['total_time'] > 60]

# Calculate the number of total orders where the total delivery time is greater than 60
total_orders_greater_than_60 = df_greater_than_60.shape[0]

# Calculate the percentage of such orders in the dataset
percentage = (total_orders_greater_than_60 / df.shape[0]) * 100

print("Percentage of orders with more than 60 minutes of total delivery time:", round(percentage, 2), "%")

Percentage of orders with more than 60 minutes of total delivery time: 10.54 %

Conclusion and Recommendations¶

Question 17: What are your conclusions from the analysis? What recommendations would you like to share to help improve the business? (You can use cuisine type and feedback ratings to drive your business recommendations)¶

Increase Customer Feedback

Need to find a way to incentives the customers to provide feedback. About 39% of the experience is not being captured. Possible solution would be to offer a discount or coupon for future service if feedback is provided. Increasing the customer feedback is going to provide a significant increase in understanding the customer experience. The current data can be used as a benchmark for comparing future results after improvements or incentives are provided.

Smartphone App Enhancements

The app should be enhanced to allow for a breakdown of the variables that are currently being captured in “Food Preparation Time”. The app should be able to begin recording the time the order was placed by the customer so this can be used in conjunction with Food Preparation Time and Delivery Time. Currently, the time the order was placed, food preparation time, and restaurant confirmation time are all captured in the same metric called “Food Preparation Time.” Knowing when the order was placed on the app, when the order is being prepared at the restaurant, and when the order was complete will help provide better insight into the impact Food Preparation has on customer experiences.
